Static Volume Provisioning with EBS (Elastic Block Storage)
step by step guide ( how we create a pv, pvc and how we attach it to a pod or to any other resource )

- first we create a voluem in our cloud provider based on our availability zone
- give volume role access to the ec2 instances (which are in our eks cluser) to mount the ebs/efs volumes
- install the csi drivers into our workstation or control plane
- create a pv (persistent volume)
- create a pvc (persistent volume claim)
- attach the pv with the pvc
- finally we attach the pvc to a pod volume and mount the volume to the pod as volumemount

These are the mandatory things to be followed while creating and mounting the pv and pvc's
- The name of the volume should be clear when we are creating a pvc
- and the name should be taken from the pv ( * 'pv is known as volume')

- name of the pvc can be anything
- name of the volume can also be anything in the pod level
- a single pvc or volume can be attached to many pods

This command lists which pods are using which volumes or claims
# kubectl get pods -o json | jq '.items[] | {pod: .metadata.name, volumes: .spec.volumes}'

Dynamic Volume Provisioning with EBS (Elastic Block Storage)
steps to be followed (for dynamic volume provisioning)

- first we install the required csi drivers
- give the required role access to the ec2 instances whcih are there in our cluster
- create a storageclass for our project (it is namespace level)
- * here we create a pvc and it creates a disk in the cloud and a pv in our cluster automatically
- it waits for a consumer like a pod (here pod or any other resource which is using the storage or pvc is a cosnumer)
- here all the process is done dynamically and provsioned the storage/volume based on the demand (pvc creation)

Static Volume Provisioning with EFS (Elastic File System)
steps to be followed

- first we create a efs volume
- give required role access to the ec2 instaces which are in our eks cluster
- enable port for the efs volume with 2049 (because it is a network storage or filesystem)
- next forward the inbound traffic from the security group of the ec2 instances of our eks cluster
- finally we push or add the files to this filesystem
